<section id="about" class="fade-in">
  <span class="sec-lbl" id="lAbout">About Meghalaya</span>
  <h2 class="sec-title" id="aboutTitle">The <em>Abode of Clouds</em></h2>
  <p class="sec-body" id="aboutBody">Meghalaya — literally "the Abode of Clouds" (Megha = cloud, Alaya = abode) — is one of the most extraordinary places on earth. This small, green-shrouded state in the northeastern corner of India receives more rainfall than almost anywhere on the planet. Mawsynram and Cherrapunji (Sohra) in the East Khasi Hills district have both held the title of the wettest place on earth — Mawsynram currently holds the record at over 11,872 mm of annual rainfall. The rain doesn't just fall in Meghalaya — it defines everything: the landscape, the culture, the architecture, the food, the very mood of the people. The living root bridges of Meghalaya are one of nature's most miraculous constructions — the Khasi and Jaintia tribes have trained the roots of the Ficus elastica (Indian rubber tree) over centuries to grow across streams and rivers, creating living bridges that grow stronger with time. The Double Decker Living Root Bridge near Nongriat village is one of India's most photographed natural structures. Meghalaya is the only major matrilineal society remaining in South Asia — among the Khasi and Garo tribes, property, family name and inheritance pass through the mother's line. The youngest daughter (Ka Khadduh) inherits the family home. This is not merely a social practice but a complete philosophical framework that shapes every aspect of Khasi and Garo life, gender relations and community structure. The state's three major tribes — the Khasi of the central and eastern hills, the Jaintia (Pnar) of the eastern hills and the Garo of the western hills — each have distinct languages, cultures, religions and traditions. Meghalaya's caves — Krem Liat Prah is one of the longest natural caves in Asia at 31 km — and its waterfalls (Nohkalikai, at 340 meters, is India's tallest plunge waterfall) create a landscape of extraordinary natural drama. This is a state where clouds live in the trees, rivers run through living bridges and the rain is not weather — it is identity.</p>
</section>
