const placesData=[
{emoji:"🌿",name:"Double Decker Living Root Bridge",location:"Nongriat, East Khasi Hills",desc:"One of India's most remarkable natural structures — the Khasi people have trained the aerial roots of Ficus elastica rubber trees across gorges for over 500 years, creating living bridges that strengthen with age. The Double Decker Root Bridge near Nongriat requires a 3,500-step descent through dense forest but rewards visitors with a sight of profound biological and human ingenuity. The bridges continue to grow — they are alive.",fee:["Rs.50 village conservation fee"]},
{emoji:"🌊",name:"Nohkalikai Falls",location:"Cherrapunji (Sohra), East Khasi Hills",desc:"India's tallest plunge waterfall — 340 meters of the Nohkalikai stream plunging into a vivid turquoise pool at the base of a cliff. The waterfall is most spectacular June-November when rainfall feeds it to maximum volume, creating a pillar of mist and thunder audible from kilometers away. The tragic love story of Ka Likai (a Khasi woman who leapt here after discovering her husband had killed her daughter) is inseparable from the waterfall.",fee:["Rs.30"]},
{emoji:"🌫️",name:"Cherrapunji (Sohra) & Mawsynram",location:"East Khasi Hills",desc:"The wettest places on earth — Cherrapunji held the world rainfall record for a century before Mawsynram (11,872 mm annual average) took the title. The landscape here is paradoxically beautiful and haunted — the cliffs drop thousands of feet to the Bangladesh plains below, clouds pour in from the Bay of Bengal and the whole world seems to be dissolving into water. Mawsmai Cave and the Seven Sisters Falls (Bangladesh viewpoint) are extraordinary.",fee:["Rs.30 Mawsmai Cave"]},
{emoji:"🏔️",name:"Dawki & Umngot River",location:"East Khasi Hills — Bangladesh Border",desc:"The Umngot river at Dawki has one of the clearest waters in the world — the river is so transparent that boats appear to be floating on air above a gravel riverbed. The Indo-Bangladesh border runs through Dawki. The suspension bridge, the weekly market and the boat rides on the glass-clear river create a surreal and beautiful experience. In winter, the water clarity is at its maximum.",fee:["Boat charges apply"]},
{emoji:"🦇",name:"Krem Liat Prah — Asia's Longest Sandstone Cave",location:"East Jaintia Hills",desc:"At 31 km, Krem Liat Prah is among the longest natural sandstone caves in Asia — a network of tunnels, chambers and underground rivers carved by water over millions of years. The cave contains extraordinary formations including stalactites, stalagmites and enormous underground chambers. The Jaintia Hills contain one of the world's highest concentrations of caves — over 1,700 recorded caves in Meghalaya alone.",fee:["Paid + guide required"]},
{emoji:"🌲",name:"Mawphlang Sacred Forest",location:"East Khasi Hills",desc:"One of the oldest surviving sacred forests in India — a 192-acre grove protected by the Khasi community for centuries under the law of the Lyngdoh (village priest). Nothing may be taken from the forest — no fruit, no flower, no fallen leaf. The trees are ancient, the undergrowth dense and the atmosphere profoundly still. The Khasi belief that the forest is the abode of the forest deity has preserved biodiversity that would otherwise have disappeared.",fee:["Rs.50 guided tour"]},
{emoji:"🌈",name:"Umiam Lake (Barapani)",location:"Ri Bhoi District",desc:"A vast reservoir lake 15 km from Shillong, surrounded by pine-forested hills that reflect in the water on clear mornings. Boating, water sports and picnics make it Shillong's most popular day destination. The drive from Shillong through Khasi pine forests to reach the lake is beautiful. At sunset when mist begins to form over the water and the hills turn violet, it is one of Northeast India's most atmospheric landscapes.",fee:["Boating charges apply"]},
{emoji:"🐘",name:"Balpakram National Park",location:"West Garo Hills",desc:"The Garo tribe's sacred landscape — a remote plateau on the edge of the Garo Hills where the land drops 3,000 feet to the Bangladesh plains. The Garos believe this is where the souls of the dead come to rest before their final journey. The national park shelters Asian elephants, tigers, red pandas, clouded leopards, binturong and over 300 bird species in dense sub-tropical forest. Rarely visited, profoundly wild.",fee:["Paid"]},
{emoji:"🌸",name:"Shillong — Scotland of the East",location:"East Khasi Hills",desc:"India's rock music capital and the only city in the Northeast built on colonial foundations — Shillong's pine forests, hill churches, colonial bungalows, Ward's Lake and the Cathedral of Mary Help of Christians create an atmosphere unlike any other Indian city. The Shillong music scene has produced more rock musicians per capita than any other Indian city. The morning mist on the pine trees and the evening concert at Police Bazaar are quintessentially Shillong.",fee:["Free"]},
{emoji:"🏊",name:"Nongriat Trek & Clear Blue Pools",location:"East Khasi Hills",desc:"The 3,500-step trek down to Nongriat village passes through waterfalls, jungle and three living root bridges before reaching the Rainbow Falls and the vivid blue natural swimming pools that have made this one of Northeast India's most celebrated treks. The pools are an extraordinary clear blue-green — carved by centuries of flowing water through limestone. The entire trek is within Khasi community-managed forest.",fee:["Village conservation fee"]}
];

const artsData=[
{emoji:"🧵",name:"Cane & Bamboo Craft",location:"Statewide — All Three Tribes",desc:"Meghalaya's three major tribes produce extraordinary cane and bamboo work — the Khasi's quiver baskets (tangkong), fish traps, carrying baskets (shnong) and furniture; the Garo's distinctive bamboo musical instruments; the Jaintia's woven mats and storage baskets. The precision of Meghalayan bamboo weaving — some baskets watertight enough to carry water — reflects accumulated knowledge spanning centuries. Shillong's Police Bazaar sells the finest examples."},
{emoji:"💎",name:"Khasi Jewelry & Silverwork",location:"East Khasi Hills",desc:"The Khasi matrilineal tradition places enormous emphasis on women's jewelry — elaborate silver necklaces (u kynthei), earrings (u krip) and the crown-like headdress (ka jainseh) worn at festivals. The craftsmanship is extraordinary: Khasi silversmiths in Shillong and Nongkrem create filigree work of great delicacy. The jewelry worn by Ka Shad Suk Mynsiem dancers — layers of gold and silver — represents an entire treasury."},
{emoji:"🥁",name:"Nongkrem Dance Drums & Music",location:"East Khasi Hills",desc:"The music of the Nongkrem festival — the tangmuri (gourd pipe), ksing (drum), bom (large drum) and duitara (string instrument) — creates a sound world entirely unique to the Khasi. The rhythms of Nongkrem are fixed, prescribed and ancient: each beat sequence is part of a ceremonial grammar that connects the living community to its ancestors and forest deities. The music is inseparable from the dance."},
{emoji:"🎭",name:"Wangala Dance — Hundred Drums Festival",location:"West Garo Hills",desc:"The Garo tribe's most spectacular cultural tradition — the Wangala festival's dance involves hundreds of men playing the dama (drum) simultaneously while performing synchronized stepping movements in traditional warrior dress. The sound of 100 Garo war drums filling a valley at dusk is extraordinary. The Wangala is simultaneously an agricultural thanksgiving, an ancestor worship and a display of community vitality."},
{emoji:"🧶",name:"Eri Silk & Traditional Weaving",location:"Khasi and Garo Areas",desc:"Eri silk — produced from the Samia ricini silkworm that feeds on castor leaves — is a distinctive Meghalayan textile tradition. Unlike mulberry silk, Eri is a 'peace silk' — the moth emerges naturally before the cocoon is processed. The resulting fabric is warm, soft and distinctively textured. Khasi and Garo women weave traditional garments on backstrap looms — the jainsem (Khasi dress) and the dakmanda (Garo outfit) are each works of careful art."},
{emoji:"🏺",name:"Pottery & Stone Heritage",location:"Jaintia Hills",desc:"The Jaintia Hills contain remarkable megalithic monuments — standing stones (menhirs), stone platforms (dolmens) and stone circles erected by Jaintia and Khasi communities as memorials to the dead and markers of significance. The Nartiang monolith field in West Jaintia Hills has one of the highest concentrations of megalithic monuments in South Asia. These traditions link Meghalaya's tribal communities to a Bronze Age heritage found across the world."}
];

const traditionsData=[
{emoji:"💃",name:"Nongkrem Dance Festival",location:"Smit Village, East Khasi Hills — November",desc:"The most sacred festival of the Khasi people — a five-day festival performed at the sacred Smit village by the Syiem (king) of the Khyriem clan and the community's young women and men. The young women wear layers of elaborate gold and silver jewelry, silk garments and perform slow, dignified dances around a sacred tree. Young men in warrior dress dance with swords and yak tails. The festival is an offering to Ka Blei Synshar (the Khasi supreme deity) for a bountiful harvest."},
{emoji:"🥁",name:"Wangala — Hundred Drums Festival",location:"Asanang, West Garo Hills — November",desc:"The harvest festival of the Garo tribe — celebrated with 100 drummers playing in unison, traditional warrior dance, rice beer (chubitchi) and communal feasting over two days. The festival is an offering to Misi Saljong (the sun god of the Garos). The sound of 100 Garo drums filling the Garo Hills is one of Northeast India's most powerful cultural experiences. Wangala represents the Garo's direct communion with the forces of fertility and harvest."},
{emoji:"🌸",name:"Behdeinkhlam Festival",location:"Jowai, West Jaintia Hills — July",desc:"The most important festival of the Pnar (Jaintia) tribe — a rain festival to drive away disease and evil spirits. Men carry enormous wooden posts called 'rath' through the streets of Jowai, then plunge them into the Myntdu river. The culminating rotumney (football) match — where teams compete to push a wooden ball across a field using long wooden sticks — is ancient, chaotic and thrilling. A festival of extraordinary communal energy."},
{emoji:"🎵",name:"Shillong Guitar Festival",location:"Shillong — November",desc:"India's rock music capital celebrates its identity every November — the Shillong Guitar Festival draws rock musicians from across Northeast India and beyond for three days of performances. Shillong has produced some of India's finest rock musicians — Lou Majaw (the Jimi Hendrix devotee who has celebrated Hendrix's birthday annually for 50 years), Soulmate, Thermal and a Quarter. The guitar here is not imported culture — it has been absorbed and made entirely Meghalayan."},
{emoji:"🌿",name:"Chad Sukra (Seed Sowing Festival)",location:"Jaintia Hills — April",desc:"The Pnar seed sowing festival — celebrated at the beginning of the agricultural year with offerings to the divine forces of fertility. The community gathers at sacred groves, the priest performs rituals connecting the planting season to ancestral blessing, and the community feasts together. Like all Meghalayan tribal festivals, Chad Sukra connects the living community to the land, the ancestors and the forest in an unbroken chain of seasonal ritual."},
{emoji:"🎶",name:"Shad Suk Mynsiem",location:"Shillong — April",desc:"The 'Dance of the Joyful Heart' — the most joyful Khasi festival, celebrating spring and the bounty of the earth. Thousands of young Khasi women dressed in full traditional regalia (ka jainsem) perform intricate group dances at Weiking Ground, Shillong, while young men in warrior dress move around them. The festival is pure celebration — no sacrifice, no solemnity, just the joy of being alive in a beautiful world. One of Northeast India's most visually spectacular festivals."}
