const cuisinesData=[
{emoji:"🍖",name:"Jadoh — Rice & Pork",location:"Khasi Heartland",desc:"The most iconic Khasi dish — red rice cooked directly with pork blood, fat, ginger and turmeric into a one-pot meal of extraordinary depth. The pork fat renders into the rice, the blood enriches the color and the ginger cuts through the richness. Jadoh is festival food, everyday food and the first thing a Khasi person in the diaspora misses. Eaten with a fried egg and green salad. Nothing else tastes like this."},
{emoji:"🌶️",name:"Tungrymbai — Fermented Soybean",location:"Khasi and Jaintia Hills",desc:"Fermented soybeans are a cornerstone of Khasi and Jaintia cooking — dried, fermented, and used as a flavor base in curries, chutneys and side dishes. The resulting tungrymbai has a profound, funky, umami depth that infuses everything it touches. Combined with mustard oil, ginger, dried fish and local chilies, it creates flavors completely unlike anything in South Asian cooking. A cuisine of moisture, fermentation and forest produce."},
{emoji:"🥩",name:"Doh Jem — Pork with Bamboo Shoot",location:"Khasi Areas",desc:"Slow-cooked pork with fresh or fermented bamboo shoot — the acid of the bamboo cut through the fat of the pork while both absorb the flavors of ginger, chili and the specific wild herbs that grow only in the Khasi Hills. This is Meghalaya's forest-to-table philosophy: the pork from village pigs, the bamboo from the surrounding forest, the herbs picked fresh from the hillside. The dish tastes of the landscape itself."},
{emoji:"🍵",name:"Pukhlein & Rice Preparations",location:"Khasi Festivals",desc:"Pukhlein — deep-fried rice flour fritters mixed with jaggery — are the definitive Khasi festival sweet, eaten at Nongkrem, Shad Suk Mynsiem and family gatherings. Meghalayan red rice (kyat u sier pdeng) has a distinctive nutty flavor from the local mountain soil. Pumaloi — steamed rice pounded to a soft cake — is eaten with savory accompaniments. The rice culture here is mountain-adapted — smaller, darker, more aromatic than lowland varieties."},
{emoji:"🐟",name:"Nakham Bitchi — Dried Fish Chutney",location:"Statewide",desc:"Dried river fish ground with chili into a pungent paste — nakham bitchi is the condiment that appears on every Khasi table with every meal. The drying concentrates the fish's flavor into something enormously intense. Mixed with fresh chili, local tomatoes and sometimes fermented soybeans, it creates a chutney of extraordinary complexity. A spoonful transforms a bowl of plain rice into a complete meal. It is the taste memory of the Khasi diaspora everywhere in the world."},
{emoji:"🥬",name:"Momo & Northeast Crossover Food",location:"Shillong",desc:"Shillong's position as the cosmopolitan capital of Northeast India has created a food culture of delightful eclecticism — Tibetan momos (dumplings) from Tibetan refugee settlements, Nepali preparations from the sizable Nepali community, Bangladeshi river fish preparations, Chinese restaurants that have been operating since the 1950s, and the pan-Northeast Indian rice beer cultures. The Police Bazaar food lanes are one of India's most genuinely diverse street food corridors."},
{emoji:"🌾",name:"Chubitchi & Rice Beer",location:"Garo Hills",desc:"Chubitchi — the Garo rice beer brewed in bamboo containers — is central to every Garo ceremony and social gathering. The brewing process uses a yeast starter (mosombai) made from local forest plants; the flavor ranges from sweet and mild to sour and complex depending on fermentation length. Like all Northeast India's rice beers, chubitchi is simultaneously a beverage, a ritual offering and a marker of cultural identity. Refusing it at a Garo festival is inconceivable."},
{emoji:"🍄",name:"Forest Mushrooms & Seasonal Produce",location:"Khasi and Jaintia Hills",desc:"Meghalaya's forests produce an extraordinary range of edible mushrooms — the red cantharellus species found in Khasi pine forests are among the finest edible mushrooms in India. Combined with the local practice of gathering wild herbs, ferns, tubers and fruits from forest commons, the Khasi food system represents a deep ecological knowledge of the landscape. The forest is not separate from the kitchen — it is the kitchen's most important ingredient."}
